give backgourd info to Help setting up terraform.tfvars and .tfbackend

------------------

ðŸ§ª 1. terraform.tfvars â€“ For Defining Variables
ðŸ” What it is:
A file that provides values for variables declared in your *.tf files. This allows you to keep your code clean and your secrets out of version control (when used properly).

ðŸ“¦ Example terraform.tfvars

region        = "us-west-2"
domain_name   = "pykesys.com"
public_key    = file("~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub")


You would then modify your main.tf or other .tf files to use:

variable "region" {}
variable "domain_name" {}
variable "public_key" {}



ðŸ’¾ 2. terraform.tfbackend â€“ For Remote State Storage (Optional, but important)
ðŸ” What it is:
Defines how and where Terraform stores its state file. Remote state enables team collaboration, locking, and backup â€” usually via an S3 bucket for AWS.

ðŸ“¦ Example terraform.tfbackend

bucket         = "pykesys-terraform-state"
key            = "ec2/pykesys-instance.tfstate"
region         = "us-west-2"
dynamodb_table = "pykesys-terraform-locks"
encrypt        = true

Then, in your code:

terraform {
  backend "s3" {}
}


And run:

terraform init -backend-config="terraform.tfbackend"


âœ… Summary Table

File	Purpose	Sensitive Info?	Checked into Git?
terraform.tfvars	Provides values for declared variables	Maybe	âŒ (use *.tfvars.example)
terraform.tfbackend	Defines backend for storing .tfstate	Yes	âŒ (never)
ðŸ“ Recommended Structure

pykesys-aws-deploy/
â”œâ”€â”€ main.tf
â”œâ”€â”€ variables.tf
â”œâ”€â”€ terraform.tfvars        # or terraform.tfvars.example
â”œâ”€â”€ terraform.tfbackend     # contains S3 backend info
â”œâ”€â”€ outputs.tf
â””â”€â”€ README.md


